<h2>Overview</h2>
<p>The <code>preload</code> attribute hints to the browser how much of a media file to download before the user presses play. It controls the tradeoff between bandwidth usage and playback responsiveness.</p>
<p><strong>Applies to:</strong> <a href="/docs/elements/native/audio/"><code>&lt;audio&gt;</code></a>, <a href="/docs/elements/native/video/"><code>&lt;video&gt;</code></a></p>

<h2>Values</h2>
<table>
  <thead><tr><th>Value</th><th>What Loads</th><th>Tradeoff</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td><code>none</code></td><td>Nothing until play is triggered</td><td>Maximum bandwidth savings; playback starts with a delay</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>metadata</code></td><td>Duration, dimensions, first frame (small download)</td><td>Good balance; UI shows duration and timeline immediately</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>auto</code></td><td>Browser decides, often buffers the entire file</td><td>Fastest playback start; highest bandwidth cost</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>""</code> (empty string)</td><td>Same as <code>auto</code></td><td>Equivalent to <code>auto</code> per the spec</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>
<p>The default when the attribute is absent varies by browser, but most treat it as <code>metadata</code>.</p>

